{"cursor":"34052","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nAn 'artificial heart valve' is a device implanted in the heart of a patient with\nheart valvular disease. When one of the four heart valves malfunctions, the\nmedical choice may be to replace the natural valve with an artificial valve.\nThis requires open-heart surgery.\n\nValves are integral to the normal physiological functioning of the human heart.\nNatural heart valves are evolved to forms that perform the functional\nrequirement of inducing unidirectional blood flow through the valve structure\nfrom one chamber of the heart to another. Natural heart valves become\ndysfunctional for a variety of pathological causes. Some pathologies may require\ncomplete surgical replacement of the natural heart valve with a heart valve\nprosthesis.\n","linknr":314,"url":"Heart_valve_prosthesis","recorded":1362511568,"links":24,"instances":["medicine","medicine","geometry","heart","unit","circulation","heart","biology","mechanics"],"pdf":["http://www.arquivosonline.com.br/pesquisartigos/Pdfs/1984/v43n6/43060007.pdf","http://www.arquivosonline.com.br/pesquisartigos/Pdfs/1984/v43n6/43060007.pdf"],"categories":["Cardiology","Cardiac surgery","Implants","Prosthetics"],"headings":["Types of heart valve prostheses","Mechanical valves","Tissue (biological) valves","Functional requirements of heart valve prostheses","Design challenges of heart valve prostheses","Replaceable models of heart valve prostheses","Typical configuration of a heart valve prosthesis","See also","References","Sources","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/09/Heartvalve.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.or